  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strategic advice to the Vietnamese Water Resources Institute regarding Water Retention Measures in the Mekong Delta</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Water retention, especially in the Upper Delta, was already indicated in the MDP as a priority given its importance for the delta as a whole system. The drought and saline water intrusion in 2016 and again 2020 have been serious wake-up calls for the Mekong Delta. In the dry season there is a serious lack of fresh water while in the wet season there is too much. To solve the drought problems, water retention is necessary but in itself cannot be the only solution. A substantial part of Delta&#x2019;s agriculture is too dependent on fresh water for production in the dry season. Drinking water supply in coastal zones is too dependent on poor quality surface water or on groundwater reserves that are hardly recharged. This assignment aims to provide strategic advice to the water retention project of the Water Resources Institute, which falls under the Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment (MoNRE). This 2-year project is called &quot;Investigation of comprehensive water retention measures to solve the water redundancy in wet season and water shortage in dry season for the sustainable development of Vietnam Mekong Delta&quot;. The project, financed by MoNRE, is expected to benefit from Dutch expertise to improve its quality and relevance for Vietnamese decision makers. This assignment is financed through the Partners for Water Program, executed by the Netherlands Enterprise Agency (RVO.nl), part of the Netherlands Ministry of Economic Affairs and Climate. The Partners for Water Program is commissioned by the Ministry of Infrastructure and Water Management on behalf of the Interdepartmental Water Cluster.</narrative>
  </description>
